data.reasoningText:
Good. I have the project structure. Bootstrap is available. Let me plan and implement.

## Component Plan

### Component Tree
```
ApplyPage                    (page — owns all form state, orchestrates steps)
├── StepIndicator            (step progress bar)
├── PersonalInfoStep         (step 1)
├── WorkHistoryStep          (step 2)
│   └── WorkEntryForm        (single work entry)
├── ReferencesStep           (step 3)
│   └── ReferenceForm        (single reference)
├── CoverLetterStep          (step 4)
└── ReviewStep               (step 5)


```

Now I'm mapping out the implementation sequence: first the data models and service interface, then the leaf components that handle individual form entries, followed by the step components themselves, the main page component, and finally wiring everything up in dependency injection. I'm thinking through the data flow where ApplyPage holds all the state and each step communicates back through event callbacks.

Actually, for a wizard form it makes more sense to use mutable view models internally so the step components can bind directly to them without constantly raising callbacks. I'll keep the immutable records for the final submission but use mutable classes during editing to simplify the binding logic.

So I need to create the models file with both the records and mutable view model classes, stub out the service implementation, and then build out the step components in the Apply folder. The ApplyPage will own instances of these mutable models and pass them down to each step.

```

csharp
public class PersonalInfoModel
{
    public string FirstName { get; set; }
    public string LastName { get; set; }
    public string Email { get; set; }
    public string Phone { get; set; }
}

public class WorkEntryModel
{
    public string Company { get; set; }
    public string Position { get; set; }
    public DateTime StartDate { get; set; }
    public DateTime EndDate { get; set; }
    public string Description { get; set; }
}

public class ReferenceModel
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public string Title { get; set; }
    public string Email { get; set; }
    public string Phone { get; set; }
}
```

Now I'm organizing the file structure with the models, service, and component files laid out.

I'll keep the application state in the main Apply page and pass it down to child components via parameters, using the mutable model classes for form binding. I'll create the models and service stub first, then build out all the step components.

